{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "The process of producing electricity from various energy sources like wind, gas, or nuclear before it enters the grid.",
      "anchor": "The starting point of the electrical supply chain.",
      "misconception": "Thinking that electricity is only generated in large-scale power stations; it also includes small-scale micro-generation."
    },
    {
      "term": "Transmission",
      "simpleDefinition": "The bulk movement of electricity over long distances at very high voltages to reduce energy loss.",
      "anchor": "The 'motorway' system of the electrical grid.",
      "misconception": "Confusing transmission with distribution, which is the local delivery of power at lower voltages."
    },
    {
      "term": "Transmission Voltages",
      "simpleDefinition": "The specific high-voltage levels used in the UK grid: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV.",
      "anchor": "The 'Big Three' high-voltage levels.",
      "misconception": "Believing that any high voltage (like 11 kV or 33 kV) is a transmission voltage; those are actually distribution voltages."
    },
    {
      "term": "kV (Kilovolt)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A unit of electrical pressure equal to 1,000 Volts.",
      "anchor": "1 kV = 1,000 V.",
      "misconception": "Underestimating the scale of transmission power by forgetting to multiply the kV value by 1,000."
    },
    {
      "term": "Micro-generation",
      "simpleDefinition": "Small-scale production of electricity, often by individual homeowners or businesses using technology like solar panels.",
      "anchor": "Local, small-scale power production.",
      "misconception": "Assuming that only the National Grid can feed electricity into the system."
    },
    {
      "term": "Photovoltaic (PV)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A method of generating electricity directly from sunlight using solar cells.",
      "anchor": "Solar panel generation.",
      "misconception": "Confusing PV (which makes electricity) with solar thermal systems (which only heat water)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Biomass",
      "simpleDefinition": "A generation method that burns organic materials, such as wood pellets or plant waste, to produce electricity.",
      "anchor": "Power from organic matter.",
      "misconception": "Thinking biomass is a fossil fuel like coal; it is considered a renewable or carbon-neutral source."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "The Big Three: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV.",
    "Generation is the source; Transmission is the long-distance carrier.",
    "132 kV is the lowest transmission voltage in the UK.",
    "Micro-generation happens at the consumer level."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Confusing 132 kV (Transmission) with 33 kV (Distribution).",
    "Believing that all high-voltage cables are part of the transmission network.",
    "Thinking that generation only refers to fossil fuels.",
    "Using the terms 'Transmission' and 'Distribution' interchangeably."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Generation Methods",
      "objective": "Identify the diverse range of methods used to generate electricity for distribution.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Electricity generation is the starting point of the supply chain. In the UK, we use a diverse mix of methods to produce the power that eventually reaches the consumer. Traditional large-scale methods include burning fossil fuels like coal, oil, and gas, or using nuclear reactors to create heat for steam turbines.",
        "We also rely on a growing range of renewable sources. These include wind and wave power, hydro-electric systems, and biomass, which involves burning organic materials like wood pellets. Additionally, photovoltaic (PV) technology generates electricity directly from sunlight.",
        "It is a common mistake to think generation only happens in massive power stations. We also include micro-generation in this category, which refers to small-scale production at the local level, such as solar panels on a domestic roof. Every one of these sources feeds the grid to begin the journey of electrical supply."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the full range of sources, from traditional fossil fuels and nuclear to renewables and small-scale micro-generation."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-5a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Transmission Voltages",
      "objective": "Identify the standard high voltages used for the transmission of electricity.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Once electricity is generated, it must be moved across the country to where it is needed. This bulk movement over long distances is called transmission. To move power efficiently and minimize energy loss, we use very high voltages. You can think of the transmission network as the 'motorway' system of the electrical grid.",
        "In the UK, there are three specific transmission voltages you must identify: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV. The unit 'kV' stands for kilovolt, meaning 1,000 Volts. For example, 400 kV is 400,000 Volts.",
        "Precision is vital here. While 132 kV is the lowest of the three, it is still classified as a transmission voltage. You must distinguish these from lower distribution voltages like 33 kV or 11 kV, which are not part of the primary transmission network. If it isn't 400, 275, or 132 kV, it isn't a UK transmission voltage."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember the 'Big Three' transmission levels: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV. Anything lower belongs to the distribution network."
    }
  ]
}

